{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_26","type":"command_execution","command":"/usr/bin/bash -lc \"rg -n \\\"15/15|100\\\\.00|dynamic-access|coverage|metadata_fix_failed|test_generation_failed|workflow status|status: failure\\\" -S .\"","aggregated_output":"./post-gen-interventions/io.javaslang_javaslang_2.0.6.md:4:Stage: metadata_fix_failed\n./post-gen-interventions/io.javaslang_javaslang_2.0.6.md:26:The generated tests exercise real dynamic features of `io.javaslang:javaslang:2.0.6`: `Lazy.val` proxy creation, typed array creation through `Value.toJavaArray`, and Java serialization proxy round-trips for persistent collections. The passing tests already validate useful reachability support, and the remaining failing serialization tests identify legitimate metadata coverage gaps rather than invalid generated behavior. Preserving the generated support keeps those successfully covered features and retains high-signal reproducers for the unresolved metadata issue.\n./forge/docs/ai-workflow-testing.md:26:- Do not treat mock repositories or synthetic libraries as workflow acceptance coverage.\n./forge/docs/ai-workflow-testing.md:109:- `metrics.code_coverage_percent`\n./forge/docs/ai-workflow-testing.md:115:Coverage and other metrics do not need a single universal threshold, but they must look credible for the library size and the generated test shape. Suspiciously low coverage, near-empty tests, or inflated metadata with weak tests should be treated as failures that need investigation.\n./forge/ai_workflows/fix_java_run_fail.py:13:    [--strategy-name \"java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5\"] \\\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:4:> [Dynamic-access workflow](../docs/dynamic-access-workflow.md) ·\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:48:- `--javac`: `javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:49:- `--java-run`: `java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4`\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:135:- Test that is fixed must maintain functional coverage. Never simplify the test to the point of triviality.\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:146:The runtime strategy integrates with `IncreaseDynamicAccessCoverageStrategy` the same way `javac_iterative` does:\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:150:  \"name\": \"java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.4\",\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:151:  \"workflow\": \"increase_dynamic_access_coverage\",\n./forge/docs/fix-java-run-fail.md:157:    \"dynamic-access-iteration\": \"prompt_templates/dynamic_access/dynamic-access-iteration.md\"\n./forge/ai_workflows/java_fail_workflow.py:39:DEFAULT_JAVAC_STRATEGY = \"javac_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5\"\n./forge/ai_workflows/java_fail_workflow.py:40:DEFAULT_JAVA_RUN_STRATEGY = \"java_run_iterative_with_coverage_sources_pi_gpt-5.5\"\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:3:description: Review pull requests with the `fixes-java-run-fail` label in graalvm-reachability-metadata. Use when asked to review or triage a PR described as `fixes-java-run-fail` or one that fixes Java/JVM runtime test failures for an existing library version update. Focus on validating the Java runtime fix, keeping the diff scoped, and ensuring dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previously tested version and the new version.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:9:These PRs repair tests, dependencies, or narrow runtime setup after an existing library version compiles, but the JVM-based test fails when it runs. Review them more lightly than `library-new-request` PRs: the library already exists, so the goal is to restore Java runtime behavior for the new version while preserving meaningful test and dynamic-access coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:17:- Be more relaxed than `library-new-request`: do not reject only because a test resembles older coverage, stays in an existing package layout, or contains compatibility branches for multiple supported versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:18:- Do not accept changes that remove meaningful test coverage just to make `java` pass.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:20:- Treat dynamic-access coverage preservation as the main quality gate. The new version should not report lower dynamic-access coverage than the previously tested version unless the PR gives a concrete, credible reason.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:21:- For numeric gates, compare the reported evidence as-is. Do not inspect generation filters, agent configuration, or metadata contents to second-guess why dynamic-access or metadata-count numbers are what they are.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:56:4. Check dynamic-access coverage across versions.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:58:   - Compare `dynamicAccess.coverageRatio`, `coveredCalls`, `totalCalls`, and the `dynamicAccess.breakdown` entries for reflection, resources, proxies, serialization, JNI, or any other present report type.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:59:   - Do not use `user-code-filter.json`, agent configuration, or metadata file contents to argue that the reported dynamic-access values are not comparable. Use the stats values as reported unless the stats are missing or stale.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:60:   - A lower `coverageRatio` or lower `coveredCalls` for the new version is blocking unless the total dynamic-access surface changed and the PR explains why the reduction is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:61:   - If `totalCalls` increases while `coveredCalls` stays flat or the ratio drops, ask for additional test coverage or metadata unless the uncovered calls are clearly outside the library behavior under test.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:69:   - Do not require an exact match. Differences are normal when upstream APIs move, generated metadata is cleaned up, or dynamic-access totals change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:71:   - When the new total is below 25% of the original and the tests and dynamic-access stats still claim comparable coverage, ask for restored metadata or a concrete explanation of the API/runtime-surface change.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:77:   - Prefer seeing the full target `test` lane green because a Java runtime fix can still reduce native-image coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:79:   - If CI is flaky but the diff and coverage comparison are sound, ask for a rerun instead of blocking on speculation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:87:- Dynamic-access coverage does not drop between the previous and new tested versions, or any apparent drop is convincingly explained by a changed upstream API/runtime surface.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:95:- Dynamic-access coverage drops without a credible explanation and replacement coverage.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:103:- The API or runtime behavior change is plausible but the PR does not explain why a coverage drop is expected.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:110:- For coverage drops: say that dynamic-access coverage must not regress between tested versions, cite the old and new values, and ask for either restored coverage or a concrete explanation.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:112:- For deleted or bypassed coverage: say that the PR fixes Java runtime execution by removing coverage and should instead adapt the test to the new runtime behavior.\n./skills/review-fixes-java-run-fail/SKILL.md:114:- For native skips that does not depend on the open-ended dynamic class loading: say that the PR avoids the failing native path instead of fixing it, so it does not demonstrate native-image runtime coverage.\n./forge/docs/architecture.md:56:        Inc[\"increase_dynamic_access_coverage\"]\n./forge/docs/architecture.md:200:| `dynamic_access_iterative` | [dynamic_acce